{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"78c21e2a-5f06-4229-8a00-886056779c91","content":"The best approach is **`dotnet-trace`** with the CPU profiling profile. From inside the container:\n\n```bash\n# Install the tool (if not already present)\ndotnet tool install -g dotnet-trace\n\n# Find your app's PID\ndotnet-trace ps\n\n# Collect a 30-second CPU trace\ndotnet-trace collect -p <PID> --profile cpu-sampling --duration 00:00:30\n```\n\nThis produces a `.nettrace` file you can analyze in **Visual Studio**, **PerfView**, or **Speedscope** (use `--format speedscope` for the latter).\n\n**Tips for K8s:**\n- If the SDK isn't in the container, copy the tool in via `kubectl cp` or use a **sidecar/ephemeral container** with the SDK.\n- Alternatively, use `dotnet-monitor` as a sidecar — it exposes an HTTP endpoint (`/trace`) to collect traces without exec'ing in.\n- For kernel-level detail (native + managed), use **`perfcollect`** or `perf`, but `dotnet-trace` is usually sufficient and much simpler.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"abccded9-60b8-4927-a814-697a1c689049","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking for guidance on collecting a CPU trace from a .NET 8 app running in a Kubernetes pod on Linux. This is a knowledge/advice question, not a code change request, so I'll answer directly.","outputTokens":334},"id":"0b1f9a06-acef-4c82-8de1-c823ca33803d","timestamp":"2026-04-05T00:53:35.350Z","parentId":"de22776a-06b2-409b-bb54-bfa3106a095b"}
